column2: people had known for hundreds of years that a potential treatment to leprosy existed in the form of something called Chaulmoogra oil. It was too thick to effectively circulate through the body
column5: was the one who FINALLY figured how to turn it into a working treatment. It’s thanks to her that a leprosy crisis was avoided in the early 1900s. Bless you
column6: Alice.Stay with me for a second because this is actual rocket science. Centaur is a second-stage rocket launcher: the workhorse of the rocket world used to propel countless probes and satellites into space. It’s been invaluable to NASA since its creation
column7: first allowing the U.S. to catch up to the Soviet Union during the space race
column8: and eventually propelling spacecrafts to land on the moon and fly by other planets in the solar system.So yes: Annie Easley helped DO that. She also contributed energy research to power plants and electronic batteries
column9: which enabled the creation of hybrid vehicles. Go ahead and thank Annie for those
column11: the impact of discrimination and its accompanying stress factors were rarely explored or acknowledged in relationship to health. She also researched the impact of racism on childhood development and ways to approach therapy that addressed the needs of people of color. And Jeanne broke a ton of ground for black psychologists through her roles in academia and her publications.Jewel researched ways to alter cell growth AND experimented with growing human tumor tissue outside of the human body to use for cancer treatment tests (instead of testing on living people). As if that wasn’t enough
column12: she also helped to form the National Science Foundation’s Committee on Women and Minorities in Science.The chair of the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission monitors the byproduct of nuclear reactors
column13: so it’s a pretty big deal. Shirley also served on a bunch of advisory boards for international security and energy
column14: AND she was the first black woman to get a Ph.D from MIT. See the full list:23 Black Female Scientists Who Changed The Damn World" True text

buzzfeed 162127458717 "2017-06-22 16:13:08 GMT" https://buzzfeed.tumblr.com/post/162127458717/the-senate-has-just-released-a-draft-of-their-very "The Senate bill to repeal and replace Obamacare makes several changes to the House bill but keeps the same skeleton
column2: including cutting almost a trillion dollars from Medicaid over a decade and letting states loosen rules on what insurance companies must cover.After being drafted in secret over the last several weeks weeks
column3: the Senate bill was finally unveiled Thursday morning. It follows the broad strokes of the House’s American Health Care Act.The Senate bill is more moderate than the House bill in some ways. While both bills offer some subsidies to help people pay for insurance
column4: the House bill did not take income into account
column5: instead basing the subsidies on age
column6: opening the door to major premium hikes for people with lower incomes.The Senate bill
column9: as Obamacare did. This should help mitigate the premium spikes projected in the House bill
column10: which could have led to some low-income elderly people facing an almost 10-fold increase in out-of-pocket costs.The Senate bill could cause a hikes in out-of-pocket costs for people who rely on the tax credit subsidies. Under Obamacare
column11: insurance companies had to offer plans that covered 70% of a person’s total health care costs to be eligible for subsidies. Under the Senate bill
column12: that would fall to 58%. In other words
column13: out-of-pocket costs for people who rely on subsidies would rise by one-third." True link
